Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Bury","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Lancashire): habitational name from Bury in Lancashire (now part of Greater Manchester), or from some other similarly named place. The placename comes from the dative case, <i>byrig</i>, of Old English <i>burh</i> ‘fortified place’.","Walloon and French: habitational name from any of several places so named, in Wallonia (Belgium) and Oise (France). The placename is from <i>Buriacum</i>, the name of a Gallo-Roman estate, composed of the personal name <i>Burius</i> + the locative suffix <i>-acum</i>. This surname is also found in the Flemish part of Belgium.","South German: variant of   Buri  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Buri","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Markus, Kurt.","Swiss German and South German: from an Alemannic pet form of the personal name <i>Burkhard</i> (see   Burkhart  ).","Italian: patronymic or plural form of   Buro  ."]},{"name":"Burgh","meanings":["English and Scottish: habitational name from one or other of the ten English places named Burgh in northern England and East Anglia, or the six named Brough in Derbyshire, Nottinghamshire, Westmorland, and Yorkshire. All these are from Old English <i>burg</i>, <i>burh</i>, Middle English <i>burgh</i> ‘massive earthwork, fortification; manor, borough’. Compare   Bury  . The placename <i>Burgh</i> is pronounced as <i>borough</i>. The surname   Brough   arose equally from places now called Burgh and Brough, and is the more common form of the surname in modern Britain, where it is pronounced <i>bruff</i> or <i>broof</i> (/brʊf/). The Scottish surname was probably brought in from Yorkshire. For the surname in Ireland see   Burke  ."]}]},{"name":"Henry","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["A perennially popular given name, of Continental Germanic origin, from <i>haim</i> ‘home’ + <i>rīc</i> ‘power, ruler’. It was an Old French name, adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain. It has been borne by eight kings of England. Not until the 17th century did the form <i>Henry</i> (as opposed to   Harry  ) become the standard vernacular form, mainly under the influence of the Latin form <i>Henricus</i> and French <i>Henri</i>."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":30,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705191,"age":55,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Henry de Bury was born in 1260, in England, his father, Sir Adam de Bury II, was 20 and his mother, Baroness Charlotte Talbot, was 15. He had at least 2 sons and 4 daughters with Margaret Radcliffe. He died on 12 October 1315, in Bury, Lancashire, England, at the age of 55."},"et":{"1260–12 October 1315":"1260–12. oktoober 1315","1260–1315":"1260–1315","1274–1300":"1274–1300","1275–1343":"1275–1343","1302–1374":"1302–1374","1313–Female":"1313–Surnud","1314–1351":"1314–1351","–1313":"–1313","–1319":"–1319","1240–1280":"1240–1280","1245–Female":"1245–Surnud","after 1280":"pärast 1280","1374":"1374","1275":"1275","1351":"1351","1274":"1274","1240":"1240","1260":"1260","1280":"1280","1290":"1290","after 